--- Mfitzsim(-at-)aol.com wrote:
> In a message dated 1/26/02 9:24:31 AM Pacific
> Standard Time, 
> nemobuscaptain(-at-)yahoo.com writes:
> 
> << Any way to adapt solex to type 4 engine? 
> Fabricate a space to put on top 
> of a progressive weber manifold?  Any other
> single carb manifold options for 
> type IV >>
> 
> VW put fuel injection on the type 3 and type 4
> in 1968; they put twin carbs 
> on the bus in 1972.  It would appear that to
> efficiently move these heavy 
> vehicles at highway speeds they decided FI or
> twin carbs were necesary to 
> satisfy the US market.
> 
> I'm sure you could find a local shop to
> fabricate an adapter for a single 
> solex by cutting and splicing together a stock
> bug manifold and an 
> aftermarket weber-bus intake manifold.
> 
> The big question is how much work, fabrication
> and $$ in manifold and preheat 
> adaptation will you go through to save how many
> $$ in carb costs?  
> 
> Then, how much performance will you have lost
> to save the $$?
> 
> When all is said and done, you might be farther
> ahead buying a cheap set of 
> used stock twin bus 34
> PDSIT's/manifolds/linkage from a 72/73/74 bus
> and 
> having the throttle shafts re-bushed.  My 74
> bus had them and they were a 
> much better quality system than most of the
> aftermarket twiin carb kits for 
> buses.
> 
> mark fitzsimons 
> Portland, OR


